04441nam a22006855i 9780691238357DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912383577 a10.1515/97806912383572doi  a(DE-B1597)609921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDT1768.K56bC73 2009 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.896/1040922221 aCrais, Clifton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSara Baartman and the Hottentot Venus :bA Ghost Story and a Biography /cClifton Crais, Pamela Scully. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b32 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tDRAMATIS PERSONAE -- tIntroduction -- t1 Winds of the Camdeboo -- t2 Cape of Storms -- t3 London Calling -- t4 Before the Law -- t5 Lost, and Found -- t6 Paris, City of Light -- t7 Ghosts of Sara Baartman -- tEPILOGUE Family -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisplayed on European stages from 1810 to 1815 as the Hottentot Venus, Sara Baartman was one of the most famous women of her day, and also one of the least known. As the Hottentot Venus, she was seen by Westerners as alluring and primitive, a reflection of their fears and suppressed desires. But who was Sara Baartman? Who was the woman who became the Hottentot Venus? Based on research and interviews that span three continents, Sara Baartman and the Hottentot Venus tells the entwined histories of an illusive life and a famous icon. In doing so, the book raises questions about the possibilities and limits of biography for understanding those who live between and among different cultures. In reconstructing Baartman's life, the book traverses the South African frontier and its genocidal violence, cosmopolitan Cape Town, the ending of the slave trade, the Industrial Revolution, the French Revolution, the Napoleonic Wars, London and Parisian high society, and the rise of racial science. The authors discuss the ramifications of discovering that when Baartman went to London, she was older than originally assumed, and they explore the enduring impact of the Hottentot Venus on ideas about women, race, and sexuality. The book concludes with the politics involved in returning Baartman's remains to her home country, and connects Baartman's story to her descendants in nineteenth- and twentieth-century South Africa. Sara Baartman and the Hottentot Venus offers the authoritative account of one woman's life and reinstates her to the full complexity of her history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aExploitationxHistoryy19th century. 0aMuseum exhibitsxMoral and ethical aspectszEurope. 0aRacism in museum exhibitszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen, KhoikhoivBiography. 0aWomen, KhoikhoizEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen, KhoikhoizEuropexSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aScully, Pamela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069123835740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691238357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691238357/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK